                  <bindingDesc resp="#BCBB">
                     <binding notAfter="1800" notBefore="1700">
                        <p>18th century ?, <placeName key="place_1000080">Italian</placeName>, perhaps all a re-creation of the late medieval quarter-binding style: wood boards with narrow inside bevel; brown leather stretching nearly halfway across each bare board (no nails), the spine cross-hatched with blind single lines, the sides tooled with blind quadruple lines in four panels; two fore-edge clasps with brown leather straps, running to shaped brass catch-plates on back cover with simple engraved patterns. <dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height quantity="222">222</height>
                              <width quantity="143">143</width>
                              <depth max="20" min="18" precision="medium">c. 18–20</depth>
                           </dimensions> (book closed). Comparable but not identical to bindings of MSS. Canon. Ital. 27, 96, and 129.</p>
                     </binding>
